<h1>
Microsoft Visual C++
</h1>
<h2>Visual C++ 2010</h2>
<h3>Tools Menu</h3>
<p>
<img alt="Visual C++" src=tool-microsoft-10-toolsMenu.png style="float:right;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:1em">
The BullseyeCoverage setup program adds a command into the Microsoft
Visual C++ <code>Tools</code> menu to enable and disable Coverage Build.
With Coverage Build enabled, build your project using command
<code>Build Rebuild</code>.
<p>
With Visual C++ 2010 Express, use the menu command <code>Tools Settings Expert Settings</code> prior to installing BullseyeCoverage.
If you already installed BullseyeCoverage before making this change, simply install again.
<p style=clear:both>
<p>
<img alt="Visual C++" src=tool-microsoft-10-tool.png style="float:right;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:1em">
If you do not see the BullseyeCoverage menu entry,
you can make this change manually using the Visual C++ menu command <code>Tools External Tools</code>.
The settings should appear as shown in the image alongside.
The <code>Command</code> setting is <code>c:\Program&nbsp;Files\BullseyeCoverage\bin\CoverageBrowser.exe</code>.
<h3><a name=2010ed></a>Executable Directories</h3>
<p>
If you find that Coverage Build does not take effect,
add <i>BullseyeCoverage</i><code>\bin</code> to the beginning of the Visual C++ <code>Executable Directories</code> setting.
The setup program makes this change to the default value for <code>Executable Directories</code>,
but you might have a custom value that overrides and cancels the BullseyeCoverage setting.
<p>
<img alt="Visual C++" src=tool-microsoft-10-propertyPages.png style="float:right;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:1em">
To make this setting manually:
<ol>
<li>Load a project
<li>Use the command <code>View Property Manager</code>
<li>Select the first property page within a configuration.
Typically this is <code>Microsoft.Cpp.Win32.user</code>.
<li>Use the command <code>View Property Pages</code>
<li>Navigate to <code>VC++ Directories</code>
<li>Edit the value for <code>Executable Directories</code>
to add the <code><i>BullseyeCoverage</i>\bin</code> directory at the beginning,
as shown in the image alongside.
<li>Press <code>OK</code>
<li>Repeat steps 3-7 for any configuration with a different first property page.
</ol>
<h2>Visual C++ 6.0 through 2008</h2>
<p>
This section applies to all editions of the products listed below.
<ul>
<li>Visual C++ 6.0
<li>Visual C++ .NET 2002
<li>Visual C++ .NET 2003
<li>Visual C++ 2005
<li>Visual C++ 2008
</ul>
<h3>Tools Menu</h3>
<p>
<img alt="Microsoft Visual Studio" src=tool_microsoft.png style="float:right;margin-bottom:1em;margin-left:1em">
The BullseyeCoverage setup program inserts a command into the Microsoft
Visual Studio <code>Tools</code> menu to enable and disable Coverage Build.
With Coverage Build enabled, build your project using command
<code>Build Rebuild</code>.
<p style=clear:both>
<img alt="Microsoft Visual Studio" src=tool_microsoft_tool.png style="float:right;margin-left:1em">
If you do not see this menu entry,
you can verify this change using the Visual Studio menu command <code>Tools External Tools</code>.
For Visual C++ 6.0, the command is <code>Tools Customize</code>, then select the tab <code>Tools</code>.
The settings should appear as shown in the image alongside.
The <code>Command</code> setting is <code>c:\Program&nbsp;Files\BullseyeCoverage\bin\CoverageBrowser.exe</code>.
<p style=clear:both>
<h3><a name=ed></a>Executable Directories</h3>
<p>
<img alt="Executable Directories" src=tool_microsoft_path.png style="float:right;margin-left:1em">
The setup program adds the <i>BullseyeCoverage</i><code>\bin</code> to the top of the
<code>Executable Directories</code> setting.
If you find that Coverage Build does not take effect,
you can verify this setting using the Visual Studio menu command <code>Tools Options</code>
then navigate to the <code>VC++ Directories</code> settings in the image alongside.
<p style=clear:both>
<h2>Microsoft Visual C++ 2005 Express</h2>
<p>
BullseyeCoverage requires <code>user32.lib</code> which is not supplied with
Microsoft Visual C++ 2005 Express.
You must obtain it yourself and place it in a directory where Visual C++ looks for libraries.
You can obtain this file from <a href="http://www.bullseye.com/pub/">www.bullseye.com/pub/</a>.
<h2>Command Line</h2>
<p>
You can build with BullseyeCoverage from the command prompt just as you normally do.
Enable coverage build with the command <code>cov01 -1</code> before building.
<p>
If you build with one of
<code>devenv</code>,
<code>msbuild.exe</code> or
<code>vcbuild.exe</code>,
you must have the <i>BullseyeCoverage</i><code>/bin</code> in the Visual Studio <code>Executable Directories</code> as described above.
<p>
If you build with Microsoft <code>build.exe</code>,
verify the <i>BullseyeCoverage</i><code>/bin</code> directory occurs first in
your <code>PATH</code> environment variable.
